 tEPILOGUE What Is the Task of Reenactment? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLong dismissed as the domain of hobbyists and obsessives, historical reenactment—the dramatization of past events using costumed actors and historical props—has only in recent years attracted serious attention from scholars. Drawing on examples from around the world, Historical Reenactment offers a fascinating, interdisciplinary exploration of this cultural phenomenon. With particular attention to reenactment’s social and pedagogical dimensions, it develops a robust definition of what the practice constitutes, considers what methodological approaches are most appropriate, and places it alongside museums and memorial sites as an object of analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aHistorical reenactmentsvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aMemory Studies, Performance Studies.1 aAdriaansen, Robbert-Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgnew, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlonso-González, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlphen, Floor van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrescó, Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarretero, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarretero, Mario, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGapps, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Álvarez, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiven, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat